    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Unfriendly Skies: What to Do?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Anna McNider suggests that NASA's aeronautics division be given proper financing to develop technologies that would significantly improve some problems in commercial air operations outlined in Sept 5 article</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Crisis for Air Traffic System: More Passengers, More Delays'' (front page, Sept. 5):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Crisis for Air Traffic System: More Passengers, More Delays'' (front page, Sept. 5):</p>
        <p>You correctly call for technological solutions, but you didn't mention that a government agency not typically associated with passenger air travel -- NASA -- could be providing that technology.</p>
        <p>The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has long been a leading innovator for American aviation. But financing for NASA aeronautics research has decreased since 1994.</p>
        <p>With proper financing, NASA's aeronautics division could be developing technologies that would significantly improve commercial air operations in inclement weather, as well as reduce noise pollution and improve safety.</p>
        <p>The future of flight in America depends on a solid base of cutting-edge technology that NASA research can provide. That research led to the first supersonic flight and could help solve the woes you so rightly describe.</p>
        <p>ANNA MC NIDER  Hampton, Va., Sept. 6, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a member of the executive committee, NASA Aeronautics Support Team, a volunteer group.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
